Task 1: Configure SELinux Policies for File Access
Subtask 1.1: Verify SELinux Status and Mode
First, let's check the current SELinux status and understand the system configuration.

# Check SELinux status
sestatus

# View current SELinux mode
getenforce

# Check SELinux configuration file
cat /etc/selinux/config
Expected Output Analysis:

Enforcing: SELinux is active and blocking unauthorized actions
Permissive: SELinux is active but only logging violations
Disabled: SELinux is turned off
Subtask 1.2: Understanding SELinux Contexts
Learn how SELinux uses security contexts to control access.

# View SELinux context of files in /etc
ls -Z /etc/passwd /etc/shadow /etc/hosts

# Check SELinux context of directories
ls -dZ /var/www/html /home /tmp

# View your current SELinux context
id -Z
Key Concepts:

User: SELinux user identity
Role: Defines what the user can do
Type: Most important for file access control
Level: Used for Multi-Level Security (MLS)
Subtask 1.3: Create Test Files and Directories
Set up a testing environment to practice SELinux configuration.

# Create a test directory structure
mkdir -p /opt/webtest/{public,private,logs}

# Create test files
echo "Public content" > /opt/webtest/public/index.html
echo "Private data" > /opt/webtest/private/secret.txt
echo "Log entry" > /opt/webtest/logs/access.log

# Check default SELinux contexts
ls -lZ /opt/webtest/
ls -lZ /opt/webtest/public/
ls -lZ /opt/webtest/private/
Subtask 1.4: Configure File Contexts
Apply appropriate SELinux contexts to secure different types of content.

# Set web content context for public directory
semanage fcontext -a -t httpd_exec_t "/opt/webtest/public(/.*)?"

# Set admin home context for private directory
semanage fcontext -a -t admin_home_t "/opt/webtest/private(/.*)?"

# Set log file context for logs directory
semanage fcontext -a -t httpd_log_t "/opt/webtest/logs(/.*)?"

# Apply the contexts
restorecon -Rv /opt/webtest/

# Verify the changes
ls -lZ /opt/webtest/
ls -lZ /opt/webtest/public/
ls -lZ /opt/webtest/private/
ls -lZ /opt/webtest/logs/
Subtask 1.5: Test File Access Controls
Create a simple test to demonstrate SELinux access control.

# Install Apache web server if not present
yum install -y httpd

# Start and enable Apache
systemctl start httpd
systemctl enable httpd

# Create a symbolic link to test directory
ln -s /opt/webtest/public /var/www/html/testsite

# Test access through web server
curl http://localhost/testsite/index.html

# Check SELinux boolean settings for httpd
getsebool -a | grep httpd | head -10
Task 2: Troubleshoot SELinux Denials with audit2allow
Subtask 2.1: Generate SELinux Denials
Create scenarios that will trigger SELinux denials for learning purposes.

# Create a script in wrong location
cat > /tmp/test_script.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash
echo "Testing SELinux"
date
EOF

chmod +x /tmp/test_script.sh

# Try to execute from httpd context (this should fail)
# First, let's create a CGI scenario
mkdir -p /var/www/cgi-bin
cp /tmp/test_script.sh /var/www/cgi-bin/

# Check the context
ls -lZ /var/www/cgi-bin/test_script.sh

# This will likely cause SELinux denial
# We'll check logs in next step
Subtask 2.2: Monitor SELinux Audit Logs
Learn to read and interpret SELinux denial messages.

# Check recent SELinux denials
ausearch -m AVC -ts recent

# Alternative method using journalctl
journalctl -t setroubleshoot --since="10 minutes ago"

# Check SELinux alerts
sealert -a /var/log/audit/audit.log

# View last 20 SELinux related log entries
grep "SELinux" /var/log/messages | tail -20
Subtask 2.3: Use audit2allow for Policy Generation
Transform SELinux denials into policy rules.

# Generate policy from recent denials
ausearch -m AVC -ts recent | audit2allow

# Generate a complete policy module
ausearch -m AVC -ts recent | audit2allow -M mypolicy

# Examine the generated policy
cat mypolicy.te

# View the policy package
ls -l mypolicy.*
Subtask 2.4: Create and Test Custom Policy
Implement a custom policy to resolve access issues.

# Create a more comprehensive test scenario
cat > /opt/custom_app.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash
# Custom application script
echo "Custom app starting..."
touch /var/log/custom_app.log
echo "$(date): Application started" >> /var/log/custom_app.log
echo "Custom app completed."
EOF

chmod +x /opt/custom_app.sh

# Run the script to generate denials
/opt/custom_app.sh

# Check for new denials
ausearch -m AVC -ts recent | tail -10

# Generate policy for this specific application
ausearch -m AVC -ts recent | audit2allow -M custom_app_policy

# Review the generated policy
cat custom_app_policy.te
Subtask 2.5: Install and Test Custom Policy
Apply the custom policy and verify it resolves the issues.

# Install the custom policy module
semodule -i custom_app_policy.pp

# List installed policy modules
semodule -l | grep custom

# Test the application again
/opt/custom_app.sh

# Verify no new denials occurred
ausearch -m AVC -ts recent | grep custom_app || echo "No denials found"

# Check if log file was created successfully
ls -lZ /var/log/custom_app.log
cat /var/log/custom_app.log
Task 3: Create Custom SELinux Policies
Subtask 3.1: Design a Custom Application Policy
Create a comprehensive policy for a custom application.

# Create application directory structure
mkdir -p /opt/myapp/{bin,config,data,logs}

# Create application files
cat > /opt/myapp/bin/myapp << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash
# My Custom Application
CONFIG_FILE="/opt/myapp/config/app.conf"
DATA_DIR="/opt/myapp/data"
LOG_FILE="/opt/myapp/logs/app.log"

echo "$(date): Starting MyApp" >> $LOG_FILE
echo "Reading config from $CONFIG_FILE" >> $LOG_FILE

if [ -f "$CONFIG_FILE" ]; then
    source "$CONFIG_FILE"
    echo "$(date): Config loaded - Debug=$DEBUG" >> $LOG_FILE
else
    echo "$(date): No config file found" >> $LOG_FILE
fi

echo "$(date): Processing data in $DATA_DIR" >> $LOG_FILE
ls "$DATA_DIR" >> $LOG_FILE 2>&1

echo "$(date): MyApp completed" >> $LOG_FILE
EOF

chmod +x /opt/myapp/bin/myapp

# Create configuration file
cat > /opt/myapp/config/app.conf << 'EOF'
DEBUG=true
MAX_CONNECTIONS=100
TIMEOUT=30
EOF

# Create sample data
echo "Sample data file" > /opt/myapp/data/sample.txt
Subtask 3.2: Define Custom SELinux Types
Create specific SELinux types for the custom application.

# Create policy source file
cat > myapp_policy.te << 'EOF'
policy_module(myapp_policy, 1.0)

# Define custom types
type myapp_exec_t;
type myapp_config_t;
type myapp_data_t;
type myapp_log_t;
type myapp_t;

# File type declarations
files_type(myapp_config_t)
files_type(myapp_data_t)
files_type(myapp_log_t)
application_executable_file(myapp_exec_t)

# Domain transition
application_domain(myapp_t, myapp_exec_t)

# Allow myapp to read its config files
allow myapp_t myapp_config_t:file { read getattr open };

# Allow myapp to read and write data files
allow myapp_t myapp_data_t:file { read write create getattr open };
allow myapp_t myapp_data_t:dir { read search getattr };

# Allow myapp to write log files
allow myapp_t myapp_log_t:file { write create append getattr open };
allow myapp_t myapp_log_t:dir { write add_name };

# Basic permissions
allow myapp_t bin_t:file { execute read getattr open };
allow myapp_t shell_exec_t:file { execute read getattr open };
EOF

# Create file context definitions
cat > myapp_policy.fc << 'EOF'
/opt/myapp/bin/myapp    --  gen_context(system_u:object_r:myapp_exec_t,s0)
/opt/myapp/config(/.*)?     gen_context(system_u:object_r:myapp_config_t,s0)
/opt/myapp/data(/.*)?       gen_context(system_u:object_r:myapp_data_t,s0)
/opt/myapp/logs(/.*)?       gen_context(system_u:object_r:myapp_log_t,s0)
EOF
Subtask 3.3: Compile and Install Custom Policy
Build and deploy the custom SELinux policy.

# Compile the policy module
make -f /usr/share/selinux/devel/Makefile myapp_policy.pp

# Install the policy module
semodule -i myapp_policy.pp

# Verify installation
semodule -l | grep myapp

# Apply file contexts
semanage fcontext -a -f -- -t myapp_exec_t "/opt/myapp/bin/myapp"
semanage fcontext -a -t myapp_config_t "/opt/myapp/config(/.*)?"
semanage fcontext -a -t myapp_data_t "/opt/myapp/data(/.*)?"
semanage fcontext -a -t myapp_log_t "/opt/myapp/logs(/.*)?"

# Restore contexts
restorecon -Rv /opt/myapp/

# Verify contexts
ls -lZ /opt/myapp/bin/myapp
ls -lZ /opt/myapp/config/
ls -lZ /opt/myapp/data/
ls -lZ /opt/myapp/logs/
Subtask 3.4: Test Custom Policy
Validate that the custom policy works correctly.

# Test the application
/opt/myapp/bin/myapp

# Check for any denials
ausearch -m AVC -ts recent | grep myapp || echo "No denials found"

# Verify log file creation
cat /opt/myapp/logs/app.log

# Test file operations
echo "New data entry" >> /opt/myapp/data/newfile.txt
ls -lZ /opt/myapp/data/

# Run application multiple times to test various operations
for i in {1..3}; do
    echo "Test run $i"
    /opt/myapp/bin/myapp
    sleep 1
done

# Check comprehensive log
cat /opt/myapp/logs/app.log
Subtask 3.5: Policy Refinement and Troubleshooting
Improve and debug the custom policy based on testing results.

# Check for any remaining denials
ausearch -m AVC -ts recent

# If denials exist, generate additional rules
ausearch -m AVC -ts recent | audit2allow

# Create an updated policy if needed
ausearch -m AVC -ts recent | audit2allow -M myapp_policy_update

# View the update
cat myapp_policy_update.te

# Install the update if necessary
# semodule -i myapp_policy_update.pp

# Verify policy status
semodule -l | grep myapp

# Test final functionality
echo "Final test data" > /opt/myapp/data/final_test.txt
/opt/myapp/bin/myapp

# Confirm no denials
ausearch -m AVC -ts recent | grep myapp || echo "Policy working correctly - no denials"
Advanced SELinux Management
Managing SELinux Booleans
# List all SELinux booleans
getsebool -a | head -20

# Check specific boolean
getsebool httpd_can_network_connect

# Set boolean temporarily
setsebool httpd_can_network_connect on

# Set boolean permanently
setsebool -P httpd_can_network_connect on

# View boolean descriptions
semanage boolean -l | grep httpd | head -5
SELinux Port Management
# List SELinux port assignments
semanage port -l | grep http

# Add custom port for HTTP
semanage port -a -t http_port_t -p tcp 8080

# Verify port assignment
semanage port -l | grep 8080

# Remove custom port (if needed)
# semanage port -d -t http_port_t -p tcp 8080
Troubleshooting Common Issues
Issue 1: Context Restoration Problems
# If contexts are not applying correctly
# Check file context definitions
semanage fcontext -l | grep myapp

# Force context restoration
restorecon -RvF /opt/myapp/

# Verify contexts after restoration
ls -lZ /opt/myapp/bin/myapp
Issue 2: Policy Module Conflicts
# Check for policy conflicts
semodule -l | grep -E "(myapp|custom)"

# Remove problematic module if needed
# semodule -r myapp_policy

# Reinstall with verbose output
# semodule -v -i myapp_policy.pp
Issue 3: Audit Log Analysis
# Detailed audit log analysis
ausearch -m AVC -ts today | grep denied

# Use sealert for human-readable suggestions
sealert -a /var/log/audit/audit.log | tail -50

# Check setroubleshoot service
systemctl status setroubleshoot
